{
  "texts": [
    "Distributional Metrics: We evaluate three distributional metrics -Energy Score (ES), Probability Integral Transform (PIT), and Expected Calibration Error (ECE).",
    "The ES[29] measures both accuracy and sharpness, with lower values indicating predictions closer to the ground truth.",
    "Perfect calibration yields uniformly distributed PIT values[30] on [0, 1], while deviations from uniformity are summarized by ECE[31], where ECE ≈ 0 denotes ideal calibration.Additionally, to evaluate safety, we compute four outcomes on the test-set: Correctly Safe (CS), Correctly Unsafe (CU), Unsafe (U), and Conservative (C).",
    "We define safety-critical rates of Unsafe (UR) and Conservative (CR):UR = U/(U + CU) × 100%, CR = C/(C + CS) × 100%UR measures dangerous failures where unsafe states are overlooked, while CR captures over-conservatism where safe states are misclassified.",
    "For each outcome, risk r emp M M D is computed from predicted clearances and compared against the groundtruth risk from d gt.TableIshows that the r emp M M D -based augmented collision model (Fig.5) surpasses the baseline (Fig.4) across all metrics: UR ↓50%, CR ↓80%, ES ↓74%, and ECE ↓20%."
  ]
}